Let me extract the float constants from the binary using perl.

{"analysis":"I need to extract float constants from the .rodata section. The .rodata starts at VA 0x480000, file offset 0x80000. So to convert VA to file offset: offset = VA - 0x480000 + 0x80000. I'll use perl to extract and interpret the bytes as floats.","plan":"1. Extract all float constants referenced in the disassembly
2. Also look at the trace function and other key functions
3. Build understanding of the scene","commands":[{"keystrokes":"perl -e '
use POSIX;
open(F, "/app/mystery") or die;
binmode(F);
my %addrs = (
  "480008" => 1, "48000c" => 1, "480010" => 1, "480014" => 1, "480018" => 1, "48001c" => 1,
  "480020" => 1, "480024" => 1, "480028" => 1, "48002c" => 1, "480030" => 1, "480034" => 1,
  "480038" => 1, "48003c" => 1, "480040" => 1, "480044" => 1, "480048" => 1, "48004c" => 1,
  "485a58" => 1, "485a60" => 1,
  "485ac0" => 1, "485ac4" => 1, "485ac8" => 1, "485acc" => 1,
  "485ad0" => 1, "485ad4" => 1, "485ad8" => 1, "485adc" => 1,
  "485ae0" => 1, "485ae4" => 1, "485ae8" => 1, "485aec" => 1,
);
for my $addr (sort keys %addrs) {
  my $va = hex($addr);
  my $foff = $va - 0x480000 + 0x80000;
  seek(F, $foff, 0);
  read(F, my $buf, 4);
  my $f = unpack("f<", $buf);
  printf("%s (foff 0x%x): float=%.10g  hex=[%s]\n", $addr, $foff, $f, unpack("H*", $buf));
}
close(F);
'
